liam.collections

Class CycleList<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • liam.collections.CycleList<T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<T>, java.util.Collection<T>

    public class CycleList<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.Collection<T>
    The CycleList class allows the user to store a list of values and retrieve the next value in a cycle. This may come in handy when writing a program like this, for example:
     
 
 ArrayList<String> people = new ArrayList<>();
 	
 people.add("Saksham");
 people.add("Beatrice");			 
 people.add("Kieran");
 people.add("Matt");
 people.add("Rohan");
 people.add("Ariq");
 people.add("Alice");
 people.add("Suyash");
 people.add("Koko");
 people.add("Zahra");
 people.add("Ben");
 people.add("Kristine");
 
 CycleList<String> teams = new CycleList<>();
 
 teams.add("North");
 teams.add("East");
 teams.add("West");
 teams.add("South");
 
 System.out.printf("%-20s%s%n", "Name:", "Team:");
 
 for (String person : people)
 
     System.out.printf("%-20s%s%n", person, teams.next());
    The program above prints each name in the people list as well as the team they are in. When teams.next() is called, the next value in the teams list is fetched.
    Author:
    Liam
